8.  Tasks will include the following: 
(i)  provide inputs for managing the logistics cell; 
(ii)  coordinate activities and tasks across the team; 
(iii)  maintain  timelines  and  report  upon  adherence  to  scheduled  milestones  and 
events; 
(iv)  facilitate communications within the team as well as with external stakeholders;  
(v)  maintain a database of contacts;  
(vi)  ensure that required administrative structures are in place and assist the team in 
fulfilling ADB administrative requirements in implementing the TA;  
(vii)  participate in office management to ensure a proper work environment for the 
team; 
(viii)  organize and maintain project files;  
(ix)  assist in preparing reports and presentations;  
(x)  lead the development of outreach and training materials such as brochures;  
(xi)  maintain a schedule of meetings and events;  
(xii)  provide meeting minutes and verify the contents with participants; 
(xiii)  facilitate the organization of meetings and events, including the development of 
agendas, arrangement of venues, and fulfillment of other logistical issues, and 
assist in identifying and confirming speakers and participants;  
(xiv)  develop a monthly TA update; and 
(xv)  undertake other tasks as required by ADB for the timely and effective completion 
of the TA.  

4.  Institutional Coordination Specialist (12 person-months, national)  

9.  The specialist should have extensive knowledge and experience regarding institutions 
and  policy,  including  in-depth  appreciation  of  the  role  and  responsibility  of  Mongolian 
government  ministries  involved  in  developing,  managing,  and  operating  various  logistics 
services. 
10.  Tasks will include the following: 
(i)  identify and liaise with key stakeholders and agencies including, as appropriate, 
MRTCUD,  Mongolian  Railway  Authority,  Ulaanbaatar  Railway  Company, 
customs, local government, freight forwarder associations and companies, and 
any other transport logistics user representatives; 
(ii)  plan  and  convene  stakeholder  consultations  and/or  focus  groups  (including 
freight  forwarder  firms)  to  solicit  ideas  and  possible  strategies  for  promoting 
interagency and intermodal cooperation; 
(iii)  prepare  recommendations  and  propose  policies  to  incentivize  cooperation 
among all modes and stakeholders; and 
(iv)  develop appropriate legal and regulatory decrees (such as government orders) 
that  can  be  issued  by  the  central  government  to  ensure  better  institutional 
coordination. 

